{{Infobox political party |country = Costa Rica |name = Cartago Agrarian Union Party |native_name = Partido Unión Agrícola Cartaginés |flag= Cartago Agrarian Union Party logo.svg |president = Juan Guillermo Brenes Castillo (deceased) |secretary_general = María de los Ángeles Brenes Fernández |spokesperson = |leader1_title = Treasurer |leader1_name = Cecilia Fernández Martínez |founder = |founded = {{Start date|1969|06|22|df=y}} |headquarters = East side of the church, in front of the CNP, Cervantes, Alvarado. |ideology = |position = |colors = Purple, White, Blue |blank1 = |blank2_title = |blank2 = |blank3_title = |blank3 = |seats1_title = Town council of Paraiso |seats1 = {{Composition bar|1|7|hex=1C86EE}} |seats2_title = |seats2 = |seats3_title = |seats3 = |seats4_title = |seats4 = |seats5_title = |seats5 = |seats6_title = |seats6 = |symbol = |website = }}
The '''Cartago Agrarian Union Party''' ({{lang-es|Partido Unión Agrícola Cartaginés}}) is a [[political party]] in [[Cartago Province]], [[Costa Rica]].
The party was founded in 1969 by Juan Guillermo Brenes Castillo. It first contested a [[Costa Rican general election, 1970|general election]] in 1970, but received only 0.5% of the vote and failed to win a seat. In [[Costa Rican general election, 1974|1974]] support for the party more than doubled, receiving 1.2% of the vote and winning its first seat.<ref name=DN>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] (2005) ''Elections in the Americas: A data handbook, Volume I'', p174 {{ISBN|978-0-19-928357-6}}</ref> Despite seeing its share of the vote drop to 1%, the party retained its seat in the [[Costa Rican general election, 1978|1978 elections]]. However a further slump to 0.8% in [[Costa Rican general election, 1982|1982]] saw the party lose its parliamentary representation.
It regained a seat in the [[Costa Rican general election, 1986|1986 elections]], receiving 1.2% of the national vote. The seat was retained in elections in [[Costa Rican general election, 1990|1990]] and [[Costa Rican general election, 1994|1994]], but a loss of support in the [[Costa Rican general election, 1998|1998 elections]] saw its share of the vote drop to 0.5%, resulting in it losing its solitary seat. A similar result in [[Costa Rican general election, 2002|2002]] saw the party remaining seatless.
